The Chronicle Brandon Moyo, Sports Reporter THE country’s premier netball league, Rainbow Netball League (RANL) successfully held its fourth annual awards ceremony on Saturday in Bulawayo where last season’s champions, Glow Petroleum were the biggest winners on the night. The champions, Glow Petroleum walked away with US$3 000 while runners up, Zimbabwe Republic Police (ZRP) received US$2 000, medals and a trophy while third placed Correctional Queens took home US$1 200. <img class="wp-image-592283 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/02/Rainbow-Amatuer-Netball-League.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/02/Rainbow-Amatuer-Netball-League.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2022/02/Rainbow-Amatuer-Netball-League-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Rainbow Amatuer Netball League Team accolades were not the only ones handed out as high performing individuals who also excelled throughout the season were honoured for their hard work, including the RANL Netball Stars of the Season. All the winners walked away with cash prizes.
With the previous season featuring 14 teams, all the participants were awarded appearance tokens on the night. The event was graced by representatives from the Ministry of Sports, Youth, Arts and Recreation and also the Sports and Recreation Committee (SRC).  Bulawayo based side, Goldreef were named Most Disciplined team while legend Perpetua Siyachitema was voted Coach of the Year. Champions, Glow Petroleum players dominated the Team of the Year.
The 2023 season will start on February 4 as the netball fraternity will be preparing for the historic World Cup set for August in South Africa which will be the first event to be held in the continent. <img class="wp-image-670702 size-full" src="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2023/01/asffhgj.jpg" alt="" width="680" height="380" srcset="https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2023/01/asffhgj.jpg 680w, https://www.chronicle.co.zw/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2023/01/asffhgj-360x200.jpg 360w" sizes="(max-width: 680px) 100vw, 680px" /> Perpetua Siyachitema Team of the year: Beaula Hlongwane -Wing Attack (Glow Petroleum), Christine Kadandara -Goal Keeper (Glow Petroleum), Edna Nyamhazha -Centre (Correctional Queens), Pauline Jani -Goal Shooter (ZRP Team), Barbra Lodi -Wing defence (Glow Petroleum), Cynthia Gamuchirai -Goal Defence (ZRP Team), Precious Shumba -Goal Attack (Support Unit).
Player (s) of the Year – Lesibani Karaso (Glow Petroleum), Precious Shumba (Support Unit)
Rookie of the Year – Lesibani Karaso
Golden Hand – Pauline Jani (ZRP Team)
Coach of the Year – Perpetua Siyachitema.
